        <Base:Descriptions>
          <Base:Description type="brief">
             the brick firing kiln
          </Base:Description>
          <Base:Description type="examine">
             This appears to be a large brick oven, better known as a kiln. The outside of the kiln is covered in a thick layer of red bricks, which are surprising cool to the touch despite the intense heat within the oven itself. This is due to the double layer of brick used to construct the large oven, ensuring that the inside maintains it’s temperate without the heat seeping out. This enlarged oven stands easily ten feet in height and likewise spreads the entire width of the entire northwestern corner it is built into. At the very bottom and very top of the kiln are several small slots that run along the length of it, which allow wisps of heat to blow out as a means to further maintain the perfect temperature instead the oven. Obviously this isn't the only means of ventilation for such a sizeable oven, but it is the only visible means, with the exception of six carved opening in the kiln's face to allow potters to insert their finished works into the super heated oven to dry.
          </Base:Description>
          <Base:Description type="look">
             This appears to be a large brick oven, better known as a kiln. The outside of the kiln is covered in a thick layer of red bricks. Four cast iron lids cover four large openings in the otherwise solid brick oven. Six carved opening in the kiln's face to allow potters to insert their finished works into the super heated oven to dry.
          </Base:Description>
        </Base:Descriptions>
